description.plain:
Maria-Cecilia Simone Kelly (b. May 7, 1997), better known by her stage name Rico Nasty, is a rapper who came straight out of Maryland, USA. Rico was born in D.C. and spent a few of her childhood years in New York and Virginia, but she’s lived most of her life in Prince George’s County, Maryland.

Rico Nasty began to blow up in mid 2016 off the hype of “Iggady (Remix)”, “iCarly”, and “Hey Arnold”. Her catchy melodic style later caught the attention of Lil Yachty who remixed Hey Arnold and brought her further attention, getting her closer to her goal of being a XXL Freshman.

Rico’s latest project is a collaboration with producer Kenny Beats, titled Anger Management.

description.plain:
After teasing a snippet of the video in mid-October of 2017 on Instagram, Rico Nasty released the song on January 9, 2018 after getting into a physical altercation with female rapper, Asian Doll.

This song is more than likely a song dedicated to rapper Asian Doll. Rico and Asian had been beefing not too long after they released a track together titled “Amigos”. Rico claimed that Asian was biting her style, and Asian Doll didn’t take the idea too lightly.

description.plain: Rage is the debut single of Rico Nasty’s sixth project, Nasty. As well as the penultimate track on the album. This record is quintessential Rico Nasty in her rock star form. Providing a steady mix of trap and screamo, Rico lashes out on those who dare test her. Known for embracing her individuality, she won’t let anyone jock her style. She won’t stand for any comparisons. If you can’t mosh with Rico, you won’t stay in her circle for long. This song is pure, unadulterated mania. And Rico is just getting started.

One can feel the pride and swagger as Rico reminds those that she gets what she wants, and she’ll look fly while doing it.

description.plain:
Rico Nasty enlists Gucci Mane and Don Toliver for “Don’t Like Me,” the third single for her debut studio album, Nightmare Vacation.

The three artists drop several sexual innuendos on this song and drop references to their lavish lifestyles over an instrumental trap beat that is solely produced by Buddah Bless. This song marks the record producer’s first time in working with any of the three artists.

On October 14, 2020, Rico confirmed this collaboration in a tweet. After posting several snippets of the song on social media, she confirmed its release date and cover art in another tweet six days later, on October 20.

description.plain: In “Brandon”, Rico Nasty pays homage to her childhood best friend, boyfriend, and the father of Cameron, her son. Rico gave birth to her son when she was 18, and Brandon, who never got to meet their child, died before she even knew she was pregnant in her senior year of high school. In this track, she details the grief, struggle, and grind of how hard she has worked to become successful over the years since he died. The song  interpolates and samples Vanessa Carlton’s 2002 smash hit A Thousand Miles.

description.plain: “Back & Forth” is a collaboration between American rappers Rico Nasty and Aminé off of her debut studio album, Nightmare Vacation. The two have previously collaborated on the song “SUGARPARENTS” on Aminé’s 2018 “EPLPMixtapeAlbum”, OnePointFive. On the track, Aminé and Rico talk about sex and relationships, and how they don’t want to deal with the “back and forth” of a talking stage. The song title was revealed in an XXL article on May 1st, 2020.

description.plain:
“BUSS” is a song by Rico Nasty, speculated to be featured on her upcoming mixtape RX. The song was first previewed on Nasty’s Instagram story on July 17, 2021. It was later previewed during Nasty’s Lollapalooza set on August 1, 2021. The song was officially announced on August 4, 2021, with a release date of August 6, 2021.

The song’s cover art was done by 6thdeity, an artist who has worked with Rico many times in the past on cover art for songs such as “Hard” and “Time Flies”.

This was first brought up on a Twitch livestream hosted by the producer Kenny Beats when he was asked about X. Kenny said that he wanted stems for this song. He never mentioned when he wanted the stems, so that is why it is unclear if this is a remix or the original version of this song.
